Introduction¶

In this assignment, I will use an artificial neural network (ANN) to identify objects in an image.

As always, I will import all necessary libraries before starting.

In [1]:

Using TensorFlow backend.

Importing and Preparing the Data¶

We must load the data before we can do anything with it, so let us do that now. Our dataset is the CIFAR10 dataset. It consists of 50,000 training examples and 10,000 testing examples. Each example is a 32 by 32 image with 3 channels, each ranging in value from 0 to 255. The images each contain one of the following ten objects: airplane, automobile, bird, cat, deer, dog, frog, horse, ship, or truck.

In [2]:
# Load the CIFAR10 dataset
data = keras.datasets.cifar10
(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test) = data.load_data()

We should divide the channel values by 255 to place them in the range of 0 to 1.

In [3]:
# Scale the data
X_train = X_train / 255.
X_test = X_test / 255.

Exploring the Data¶

Let us take a look at the data.

In [4]:
sns.set_style('white') # Set the plotting style
ax = plt.figure(figsize=(18, 18)) # Create the axes

# Plot the images
for i in range(100):
    plt.subplot(10, 10,i+1)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    plt.imshow(X_train[i])
    plt.xlabel(y_train[i][0])

We see a wide variety in our classes, with automobiles ranging from sedans to semi trucks and birds ranging ducks to emus - with a disturbing number of cassowaries. This should provide a good basis for understanding each of our classes.

In [5]:
# Make certain the label vectors are in the right format
y_train = to_categorical(y_train)
y_test = to_categorical(y_test)

The Initial Model¶

We will be using a simple model to start. It will flatten our inputs, put them through a single hidden dense layer with 30 nodes, and then output. We should also set our label vectors to the right format.

In [6]:
# Construct the model
nn_mdl = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(32, 32, 3)),
    keras.layers.Dense(30, activation=tf.nn.sigmoid),
    keras.layers.Dense(10, activation=tf.nn.sigmoid)
])

Now we can train our model on the training set. We will use the categorical cross entropy as our loss function, and ADAM as our training method.

In [7]:
# Define the training and evaluation process
nn_mdl.compile(optimizer='adam',
               loss='categorical_crossentropy',
               metrics=['accuracy'])
In [8]:
# Train the neural network
nn_mdl.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10)

Improving the Model¶

Let us try to improve the model. I will do this by converting it to a convolutional neural network. Features will be extracted with two convolutional layers, each followed by a maximum pooling layer. This will then feed into a simple multilayer perceptron after being flattened - two hidden layers with 100 nodes each.

In [41]:
# Construct the model
nn_mdl = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32,
                        kernel_size=(3, 3),
                        strides=(1, 1),
                        padding='same',
                        activation=tf.nn.relu,
                        input_shape=(32, 32, 3)),
    keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2),
                              strides=(2, 2)),
    keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32,
                        kernel_size=(3, 3),
                        strides=(1, 1),
                        padding='same',
                        activation=tf.nn.relu,
                        input_shape=(32, 32, 3)),
    keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2),
                              strides=(2, 2)),
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(32, 32, 3)),
    keras.layers.Dense(100, activation=tf.nn.relu),
    keras.layers.Dense(100, activation=tf.nn.relu),
    keras.layers.Dense(10, activation=tf.nn.softmax)
])

Let us train this model on our training set, using the same process as the original.

In [42]:
# Define the training and evaluation process
nn_mdl.compile(optimizer='adam',
               loss='categorical_crossentropy',
               metrics=['accuracy'])
In [43]:
# Train the neural network
nn_mdl.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10)

Conclusions¶

We built and tested two neural networks on the CIFAR10 dataset. The first was a single layer perceptron, and the second a convolutional neural network. What was not shown here was the dozen or so intermediary networks I constructed and tested. Here is what I learned from this process:

  • Deeper neural networks tend to perform better, but have a greater propensity for overfitting.
  • Adding more layers or more nodes is no substitute for properly structuring the network so that it can extract better features. The leap in performance I saw between a large multilayer perceptron and a smaller convolutional neural network was massive.
  • Neural networks are not nearly as intimidating as everyone makes them seem. As with most advanced mathematics, it's less magic and more trial and error, instinct, and compute time.

This was a particularly fun assignment.
